All loci. Locus 2 East Round Reservoir/Settling Basin, Locus 3 Channel in the South next to Locus 2, Locus 4 South Wall Lower Temenos Build-Up, Locus 5 South Arch Springer Wall, Locus 6 East Wall shared with the west wall of Trench 82 of 2001, Locus 7 West Stairway Wall, and Locus 8 South Wall Earlier Stage.
Major destruction level marked by collapse and the accumulation of fill and debris.
Closing elevation: west 894.721 m, north 894.814 m, and east 894.848 m.
Phase XII: Robbing and abandonment continue.
Phase XI: Further collapse post-CE 5th c. Possibly the result of the earthquake of CE 512.
Opening elevation: At the elevation of the Lower Temenos approximately 897.246 m.

Phase IX: Major CE 363 earthquake leads to the collapse of the south gallery cryptoporticus of the Propylaeum West. The temple north colonnade falls from south to north across the Propylaeum, damage is incurred on the Propylaeum Retaining Wall and the entire area is overburdened with soil and debris.

The soil is comprised of a Munsell Weak Red 2.5YR 6/3 color, which in some areas was compacted, however, in the upper levels it was a powdery and irregular sandy matrix with randomly distributed stones. Obviously there had been appreciable water erosion that had worked on this sediment.
Phase XIII: Major collapses continue into the Islamic period.
Phase X: Site abandonment post major collapse dating to the Byzantine period from the CE 4th through 5th c.
